questions.explanation:
The SCP approach is the preventive enforcement mechanism. The SCP uses condition keys like iam:PermissionsBoundary to require that CreateRole/CreateUser requests include a specific boundary ARN. If the caller omits the boundary, the API call is denied at the Organization boundary.

Example SCP condition:
```
"Condition": {
  "StringNotEquals": {
    "iam:PermissionsBoundary": "arn:aws:iam::ACCOUNT:policy/RequiredBoundary"
  }
}
```

Option B (Config auto-remediation) is detective, not preventive — a window of risk exists. Option C (Service Catalog) is valid but optional; it doesn't prevent CLI/console/Terraform-direct creation. Option D is wrong — boundaries can be enforced.

The subtle exam value: IAM condition keys like iam:PermissionsBoundary are less well-known than general condition keys. The exam tests whether you know this specific lever exists for enforcing boundary application.
